-- China, India, Malaysia, Taiwan, Thailand: Asian Bonds, Currencies Preview
-- David Yong
-- 2010-07-25T22:48:26Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-25/china-india-malaysia-taiwan-thailand-asian-bonds-currencies-preview.html

          
          
             The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  
 Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary  Yoshito Sengoku  will hold
media briefings at 11 a.m. and 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  
 Tokyo Stock Exchange Chief Executive Officer  Atsushi Saito 
will have a press briefing at 2 p.m. in Tokyo.  
 Hiromasa Yonekura , chairman of Sumitomo Chemical Co. and
chairman of Japan’s Business Federation, or Keidanren, will hold
a media briefing at 3:30 p.m. in Tokyo.  
 The Ministry of Finance will release at 8:50 a.m. in Tokyo
its report on the trade balance for June. The surplus probably
widened to 690.9 billion yen ($7.9 billion) from a revised 320.9
billion yen in May, according to a Bloomberg News survey of
economists.  
 The yield on the 1.1 percent government bond due in June
2020 was 1.065 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  
 The yen traded at 87.54 per dollar at 7:48 a.m. in Tokyo.  
 China: China Development Bank will sell 20 billion yuan
($2.95 billion) of five-year bonds today. The government will
auction 28 billion yuan of 30-year bonds on July 28. The notes
yielded 4.03 percent at the previous sale on June 18.  
 The yield on the 2.53 percent note due in June 2015 was
2.549 percent. The yuan was at 6.7803 per dollar.  
 India: The central bank will raise its benchmark reverse
repurchase rate to 4.25 percent from 4 percent at a policy
meeting tomorrow, according to the median forecast in a
Bloomberg News survey.  
 The government may sell bonds this week with maturities
ranging from five to 20 years.  
 The yield on the 7.8 percent note due in May 2020 was 7.68
percent. The rupee was at 46.945.  
 Malaysia: The central bank will sell 2 billion ringgit
($624 million) of 91-day notes today. The debt yielded 2.785
percent on July 21. The government will auction 3.5 billion
ringgit of September 2017 bonds on July 29. The notes were first
sold on March 12 at 4.012 percent.  
 The yield on the 3.835 percent debt maturing in August 2015
was 3.40 percent, according to Bursa Malaysia. The ringgit was
at 3.1975.  
 Philippines: The government will today sell a total of 8
billion pesos ($172 million) of bills maturing in 91, 182 and
364 days. It will report its trade balance for May tomorrow.
Imports exceeded exports by $846 million in April.  
 The yield on the 7.75 percent debt due in February 2020 was
7.66 percent. The peso was at 46.315 per dollar.  
 Singapore: Industrial production probably expanded 38.4
percent in June from a year earlier, following a 58.6 percent
increase in May, according to a Bloomberg News survey before a
government report at 1 p.m. local time today.  
 The yield on the 3.25 percent bond due in September 2020
was 2.25 percent. The Singapore dollar was at S$1.3710.  
 Taiwan: The central bank will report money-supply growth
statistics for June today. The Council for Economic Planning and
Development will release the leading index for June tomorrow.
The index, a gauge of the economy three months ahead, climbed
0.3 percent in May from April.  
 The yield on the 1.375 percent note due in March 2020 was
1.392 percent. The Taiwan dollar was at NT$32.152.  
 Thailand: The central bank will tomorrow sell a total of 50
billion baht ($1.55 billion) of bills maturing in 28, 91 and 182
days. The government will sell 11 billion baht of 2029 bonds on
July 28.  
 The yield on the 3.625 percent note maturing in May 2015
was 2.97 percent. The baht was at 32.26.  
